  "text": "The rank 2 classification (K2) essentially encapsulated the primary and secondary glioblastoma clinical classes (Fig. 2B) , 19 of 20 primary glioblastomas (identified by blue bar to right) being assigned to one cluster (K2-1) and 14 of 17 secondary glioblastomas (orange bar) assigned to the other (K2-2). The concordance between unsupervised classification and clinical class was better than that achieved by unsupervised hierarchical clustering, which was driven predominantly by gain of ch7 and loss of ch10 in the primary glioblastomas, consistent with what has been described for the genetic subgrouping of primary glioblastoma [CITATION_1] , as well as loss of ch19 in the secondary glioblastomas ( Supplementary Fig. S4 ). Alteration of chromosome 19 shows an additional insight made by applying gNMR to our data set. As reflected in the skyline recurrence plot (Fig. 1) , it has been established that chromosome 19 can be gained or lost in glioblastoma. Using gNMF, we show that gain of ch19 is frequent and exclusive to primary glioblastoma and, unexpectedly, tracks closely with gain of ch20 (Fig. 2B) . In contrast, loss of ch19 is a feature of the K2-1 genetic subgroup, almost exclusive to secondary Figure 2 . Primary and secondary glioblastomas clustered by gNMF. A, gNMF of aCGH profiles finds stable clustering for ranks 2 and 3 but not for ranks 4 or higher, suggesting up to three natural subgroups (color plots ). Consensus matrices show how often samples are assigned to the same clusters during 1,000 repetitions of NMF, computed at K = 2 to 8 for 37 primary and secondary glioblastoma aCGH profiles. Each pixel represents how often a particular pair of samples cluster together, colored from 0% (deep blue , samples are never in the same cluster) to 100% (dark red, samples are always in the same cluster). Ranks 2 and 3 show largely stable assignments into 2 and 3 blocks, respectively, whereas rank 4 is disrupted (top ). B, unsupervised clustering of aCGH profiles by gNMF, Rank K = 2, largely recapitulates clinically defined primary and secondary glioblastoma subgroups. Heat map plot shows genomic gain/amplification (red ) and loss/deletion (green ) for each sample. Three secondary and one primary samples are clustered to contrary groups. glioblastoma, with gain of ch20 rarely seen in this subgroup. The strong correlation between genomic profile and clinical class strongly supports the view that the pathogeneses of these classic clinical subgroups are driven by a large number of distinct genetic events.",
